Price Subsidies, Diagnostic Tests, and Targeting of Malaria Treatment: Evidence
 from a Randomized Controlled Trial
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Cohen et al (2015): Overview
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Usually, the targeting tradeoff is that people who know they are ineligible
 may try to mimic the deserving types in order to gain access to the transfer.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
What if incentives are aligned (government and households agree on who should
 receive the transfer) but households don't know whether they're eligible?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Here: Malaria treatments: artemisinin combination therapies (ACT)
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Huge benefits if have malaria.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
no direct benefits if don't have malaria, people don't learn real reason
 they're sick, speeds up development of parasite's resistence.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
But people who are sick don't know for sure whether they have malaria (or
 something else) so many people take malaria treatments just in case.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Experiment in Kenya to test impact of 
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
better diagnosis technology
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
subsidies for ACTs
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Cohen et al (2015): Setting
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Malaria causes 200 million illnesses, kills 600K people a year
\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Many countries (ncluding Kenya) provide ACTs for free at public health facilitie
s if diagnosed with malaria.
 But...
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
diagnosis often incorrect
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
stockouts common
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Have to pay fees, travel far, line up, etc...
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Many households go to private drugstores to get ACTs or other over-the-counter
 medications (40–97% of the market!)
\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Large subsidies to ACTs to improve access.
 Subsidy 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim95\%$
\end_inset

 of cost 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Cohen et al (2015): Model
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
When households receive an illness shock they pick an action 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
a\in\begin{cases}
h & \text{seek diagnosis at a formal health facility}\\
s & \text{buy ACTs at a shop}\\
n & \text{buy non-ACT drugs or do nothing}
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Households who fall ill form a subjective probability that the illnes is
 malaria with probability 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
V^{a}\left(\pi\right) & =\pi\left[U_{P}^{a}\left(\pi\right)-p_{P}^{a}\left(\pi\right)\right]+\left(1-\pi\right)\left[U_{N}^{a}\left(\pi\right)-p_{N}^{a}\left(\pi\right)\right]\\
 & =\pi V_{P}^{a}\left(\pi\right)+\left(1-\pi\right)V_{N}^{a}\left(\pi\right)
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 denotes malaria-positive, 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 malaria negative.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Assume value of acting increasing with 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial\left(V^{a}\left(\pi\right)-V^{n}\left(\pi\right)\right)/\partial\pi>0$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in\left\{ h,s\right\} $
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Go to the drug shop iff
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
V^{s}\left(\pi\right)>\max\left\{ V^{h}\left(\pi\right),V^{n}\left(\pi\right)\right\} 
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

